I was recently listening to [Software Engineering Daily](https://softwareengineeringdaily.com/), and caught [this interview](https://softwareengineeringdaily.com/2017/03/31/webassembly-with-brendan-eich/) with [Brendan Eich](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brendan_Eich), creator of JavaScript and co-founder of Mozilla.
In it he discusses his vision for the future of the web, including his work on [WebAssembly](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WebAssembly) (a faster web language) and [Brave](https://brave.com/) (a new browser).
Brave sounded interesting: it automatically blocks all trackers, mediated ads, and cookies, and [replaces the ads](https://brave.com/about_ad_replacement.html) with its own.

##Security

Blocking ads prevents malware spread through [malvertising](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malvertising).
Trackers and cookies log your activities and follow you across sites.
Brave blocks these and prevents companies from gathering data about you.
Brave also integrates [HTTPS everywhere](https://www.eff.org/https-everywhere), which attempts to encrypt your traffic over [https](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTPS) if its supported on a given website.

Brave monetizes through BitCoin to further [enhance security](http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/telecom/internet/can-braves-bitcoin-payment-platform-save-online-publishing).
The Brave browser you download is the only application that keeps track of browsing history (unlike [Chrome](https://www.quora.com/Does-Google-Chrome-track-the-websites-users-visit-even-after-deleting-the-browser-history)).
This makes it difficult to send money online, but Brave solves this through the use of BitCoin and [Anonize](https://anonize.org/) (a protocol used to shield BitCoin transactions).

> “We don’t want to be a tracker. We don’t want that data. It’s better that we can’t have it than that we could have it and promise to be good,” [says Eich](http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/telecom/internet/can-braves-bitcoin-payment-platform-save-online-publishing).

Brave ads are also more secure than normal ads, while using less of your personal information.

> "The ad matching happens only on your device...we can have a catalog to download...[then Brave] can come up with keywords to match against. Again, if the user of Brave doesn’t opt
into this, none of this happens...In the Brave philosophy, we keep your data local. It’s encrypted if it goes anywhere near servers
that we control, and it’s encrypted with your key, not ours." [Brendan Eich](https://softwareengineeringdaily.com/2017/03/31/webassembly-with-brendan-eich/)

Like Chrome and Firefox, [Brave is open source](https://github.com/brave).

Brave doesn't make you completely anonymous on the web.
If you want to hide your IP, you should look into a [VPN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_private_network) or [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/about/overview.html.en).
Ensure you have never been [pwned](https://haveibeenpwned.com/), and be wary of the websites you give your info.
Consider using [Signal](https://whispersystems.org/) (a secure MMS replacement) or other messaging services that utilize [end-to-end encryption](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/End-to-end_encryption).
And of course, do not reuse passwords across sites.
I use [KeePass](http://keepass.info/) to keep track of all my unique passwords, but [LastPass](https://www.lastpass.com/) and [1password](https://1password.com/) are good alternatives too.

##Monetization

Some people [don't like the ad replacement model](https://brave.com/blogpost_4.html), but it sounds like it could be great for users and publishers.
Ads that are manually placed by publishers/content creators are left alone (e.g. a static image in the site, amazon affiliate link, shoutout in a podcast), only those that go through the slow loading and [fradulent](http://adage.com/article/digital/ana-report-7-2-billion-lost-ad-fraud-2015/302201/) digital ad mediation industry are replaced.
Once a user has seen/clicked a Brave ad, the revenue is divided up in the following manner.

